  '5fc26d9b-6f06-493b-9d19-fd2b628d89cb',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$tRPC — End-to-End Type Safety, Procedure Types, and React Query Integration$escape$,
  $escape$tRPC eliminates the REST/GraphQL schema layer entirely — your router IS the contract. Define procedures on the server using `publicProcedure.input(z.object({...})).query()` or `.mutation()`, and TypeScript propagates those exact types to the client with zero codegen.

Three procedure types exist: `query` (GET-like, cached), `mutation` (write operations), and `subscription` (WebSocket streams via `observable()`). Each accepts a Zod schema for input validation that doubles as your runtime guard and static type source.

The React Query integration is first-class: `trpc.post.byId.useQuery({ id: 1 })` returns a fully-typed `UseQueryResult` — no manual typing, no `as` casts. Mutations use `trpc.post.create.useMutation()` with `onSuccess` receiving the inferred return type. Under the hood, `@trpc/react-query` wraps TanStack Query, so `queryKey` management, invalidation via `utils.post.byId.invalidate()`, and optimistic updates all work natively. Procedure input errors surface as typed `TRPCClientError` with the Zod issue shape intact, letting you map field errors precisely in forms.$escape$,
  $escape$// server/router.ts
const postRouter = router({
  byId: publicProcedure
    .input(z.object({ id: z.number() }))
    .query(({ input, ctx }) => ctx.db.post.findUnique({ where: { id: input.id } })),

  create: publicProcedure
    .input(z.object({ title: z.string().min(1), body: z.string() }))
    .mutation(({ input, ctx }) => ctx.db.post.create({ data: input })),
});

// client/PostDetail.tsx
const { data, isLoading } = trpc.post.byId.useQuery({ id: 42 });
const create = trpc.post.create.useMutation({
  onSuccess: () => utils.post.byId.invalidate(),
});$escape$,
  $escape$typescript$escape$,
