INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '53bea348-7991-483c-bb60-0bf20824bc8b',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$tRPC API Versioning — Router Namespacing Over URL Paths$escape$,
  $escape$tRPC doesn't expose REST paths, so URL versioning (/v1/, /v2/) and header-based versioning are non-starters — the transport layer is HTTP but the contract is TypeScript. Version your API by namespacing routers instead.

Create sibling routers under your root appRouter: v1 and v2 sub-routers. Clients call trpc.v2.getUser.query() instead of trpc.v1.getUser.query(). Old procedures stay alive until clients migrate, giving you coexistence without HTTP gymnastics.

For backward compatibility within a version, lean on Zod's .optional() and .default() on inputs — add fields without breaking existing callers. For outputs, extend rather than mutate: add properties, never remove or rename. tRPC's end-to-end inference catches breakage at compile time, not runtime.

Deprecate gracefully with .meta({ deprecated: true }) and a custom middleware that logs or warns on deprecated calls. When a procedure is safe to remove, delete the router key — TypeScript will immediately surface every client call site that needs updating, making the migration surface area explicit and compiler-enforced.$escape$,
  $escape$import { router, publicProcedure } from './trpc';
import { z } from 'zod';

const v1 = router({
  getUser: publicProcedure
    .input(z.object({ id: z.string() }))
    .query(({ input }) => getUserById(input.id)),
});

const v2 = router({
  getUser: publicProcedure
    .input(z.object({ id: z.string(), includeProfile: z.boolean().default(false) }))
    .query(({ input }) => getUserById(input.id, input.includeProfile)),
});

export const appRouter = router({ v1, v2 });
// Client: trpc.v2.getUser.query({ id: '1', includeProfile: true })$escape$,
  $escape$typescript$escape$,
